AC Unit
AC Unit refers to the central air conditioning system or room air conditioners that cool and heat spaces.<SEP>The AC unit involves mechanical and electrical components that are used to cool indoor spaces. This includes fan motors, compressor, thermostat, etc.

Circuit Breaker
A circuit breaker serves as a safety device in the electrical system of an AC unit, which can be manually reset when it trips due to a fault.

Thermostat
The thermostat controls the temperature settings for cooling and heating in an AC system. It communicates with other components like fan motors and compressors.

Refrigerant Manifold Gauge Set
This tool is used to measure the refrigerant pressure inside an AC unit during servicing or diagnosing issues.

Soap Bubble Solution
A simple, non-toxic solution used in detecting leaks on the AC system by applying it on connection points and observing if bubbles form, indicating a leak.

Electronic Leak Detector
An instrument that can detect refrigerant leaks with precision using specialized sensors.

Start Capacitor
The capacitor assists in starting the fan motor when the AC system turns on. There may be a separate start and run capacitor in some units.

Run Capacitor
Similar to the Start Capacitor, this component is crucial for maintaining the speed of the fan motor during normal operation.

Multimeter
A multi-functional tool used by technicians for measuring electrical parameters like voltage and capacitance. It's essential for diagnosing issues with capacitors or testing connections.

AC Unit Nameplate
The nameplate provides specifications of the AC unit, including refrigerant type and amount needed for recharging, which helps in determining correct operation.

Transformer
Transformer is a device used for converting electrical energy from one voltage level to another. It plays a crucial role in AC circuits.

Fan
The Fan is an essential component of both indoor and outdoor units in AC systems, responsible for moving air through the cooling process.
